04521nmm a2200697Ia 9780520935518DE-B159720240326120151.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||240326t20012001cau    fo  d z      eng d  a97805209355187 a10.1525/97805209355182doi  a(DE-B1597)647743  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  acaucUS-CA 4aRC552.O25bB63 2001eb 7aSOC0220002bisacsh04a616.3/98/00192211 aBraziel/LeBesco, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aBodies out of Bounds :bFatness and Transgression /cBraziel/LeBesco; ed. by Jana Evans Braziel, Kathleen LeBesco. 1aBerkeley, CA : bUniversity of California Press, c[2001] 4c©2001  a1 online resource (368 p.) :b6 black-and-white photographs, 1 line illustration  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aSince World War II, when the diet and fitness industries promoted mass obsession with weight and body shape, fat has been a dirty word. In the United States, fat is seen as repulsive, funny, ugly, unclean, obscene, and above all as something to lose. Bodies Out of Bounds challenges these dominant perceptions by examining social representations of the fat body. The contributors to this collection show that what counts as fat and how it is valued are far from universal; the variety of meanings attributed to body size in other times and places demonstrates that perceptions of corpulence are infused with cultural, historical, political, and economic biases. The exceptionally rich and engaging essays collected in this volume question discursive constructions of fatness while analyzing the politics and power of corpulence and addressing the absence of fat people in media representations of the body.The essays are widely interdisciplinary; they explore their subject with insight, originality, and humor. The contributors examine the intersections of fat with ethnicity, race, queerness, class, and minority cultures, as well as with historical variations in the signification of fat. They also consider ways in which "objective" medical and psychological discourses about fat people and food hide larger agendas. By illustrating how fat is a malleable construct that can be used to serve dominant economic and cultural interests, Bodies Out of Bounds stakes new claims for those whose body size does not adhere to society's confining standards.  aIssued also in print.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 26. Mrz 2024) 0aBody imagexMiscellaneaxSocial aspects. 0aBody imagexSocial aspectsvMiscellanea. 0aDiscrimination against overweight personsvMiscellanea. 0aDiscrimination against overweight personsxMiscellanea. 0aDiscrimination fondée sur l'apparence physique. 0aDiscrimination à l'égard des obèses. 0aFemmes obèsesxAspect social. 0aImage du corpsxAspect social. 0aObesityxMiscellaneaxSocial aspects. 0aObesityxSocial aspectsvMiscellanea. 0aObésitéxAspect social. 0aOverweight womenxMiscellaneaxSocial aspects. 0aOverweight womenxSocial aspectsvMiscellanea. 0aPhysical-appearance-based biasvMiscellanea. 0aPhysical-appearance-based biasxMiscellanea. 4aPopular Culture. 4aSocial Science. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Popular Culture.2bisacsh1 aEvans Braziel, Jana, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aLeBesco, Kathleen, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt0 cprintz978052022585540uhttps://doi.org/10.1525/978052093551840uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780520935518423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780520935518/original  aEBA_UCA_YUP  aGBV-deGruyter-alles